{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Abstract\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The structural integrity of Buddhist canonical literature often reflects a sophisticated intersection of cosmological mapping, soteriological intent, and mnemonic tradition. This article argues that the number twenty-eight functions as a deliberate architectonic principle across both Therav\u257 ?da and Mah\u257 ?y\u257 ?na traditions, serving not merely as a quantitative measure but as qualitative scaffolding aligning textual bodies with cosmic order. The prevalence of twenty-eight-chapter structures in the {\i Lotus S\u363 ?tra} and A\u347 ?vagho\u7779 ?a\u8217's {\i Buddhacarita}, the enumeration of twenty-eight Buddhas in the {\i Buddhava\u7747 ?sa}, and the classification of twenty-eight material qualities ({\i r\u363 ?pa}) in the Abhidhamma suggests intentional numerological architecture rather than editorial coincidence. Drawing on the astronomical significance of the twenty-eight {\i nak\u7779 ?atras} (lunar mansions), this study proposes a novel \u8220"Ideal Canon Hypothesis\u8221": that an original twenty-eight-chapter {\i Dhammapada} may have existed, with evidence of structural merger preserved in the anomalously long twenty-sixth chapter ({\i Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?avagga}). This pan-Buddhist numerological framework connects disparate traditions through a shared symbol of totality, bridging the mundane cycles of the heavens with the supramundane path to liberation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords}: Buddhist numerology, Lotus Sutra, Dhammapada, twenty-eight Buddhas, nak\u7779 ?atras, Abhidhamma, textual criticism, pan-Buddhist architecture\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 1. Introduction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Twenty-eight. The number appears too often to be coincidence. In traditions where oral transmission preceded written codification, structural features served mnemonic, liturgical, and cosmological functions simultaneously. Within Buddhist canonical literature, one numerical pattern recurs with striking consistency: the number twenty-eight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This number appears across traditions and genres:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\b Lotus S\u363 ?tra} ({\i Saddharmapu\u7751 ?\u7693 ?ar\u299 ?ka}) in Kum\u257 ?raj\u299 ?va\u8217's definitive translation (406 CE) comprises twenty-eight chapters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\b Buddhava\u7747 ?sa} chronicles twenty-eight {\i Samm\u257 ? Sambuddhas} (Perfectly Enlightened Ones)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\b Buddhacarita} of A\u347 ?vagho\u7779 ?a contains twenty-eight cantos\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\b Abhidhamma} classifies exactly twenty-eight types of {\i r\u363 ?pa} (material form)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\b Mah\u257 ?saddan\u299 ?ti}, a major P\u257 ?li grammatical treatise, spans twenty-eight chapters\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The convergence of this number across Therav\u257 ?da scholasticism, Mah\u257 ?y\u257 ?na scripture, and Sanskrit epic poetry suggests more than coincidence. This article proposes that twenty-eight functions as a symbol of {\b cosmological totality}, derived from the twenty-eight {\i nak\u7779 ?atras} (lunar mansions) that structured Indian astronomical and calendrical systems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Furthermore, this study advances a novel hypothesis: that the P\u257 ?li {\i Dhammapada}, currently preserved in twenty-six chapters, may represent a {\b contracted form} of an original twenty-eight-chapter text. Evidence for this hypothesis includes the anomalous length of the final chapter ({\i Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?avagga}, 41 verses), the absence of a dedicated {\i Nibb\u257 ?navagga} despite Nirv\u257 ?\u7751 ?a being the central soteriological goal, and comparative analysis with the Sanskrit {\i Ud\u257 ?navarga} (which preserves distinct Nirv\u257 ?\u7751 ?a and Tath\u257 ?gata chapters).\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 2. The Astronomical Foundation: Twenty-Eight Nak\u7779 ?atras\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The significance of twenty-eight in the Indian subcontinent is rooted in ancient astronomical observation. The Indian celestial system identified twenty-eight {\i nak\u7779 ?atras}\u8212-distinct constellations through which the moon passes during its sidereal month of approximately 27.32 days. The inclusion of an intercalary mansion (often Abhijit, located between Uttar\u257 ?\u7779 ?\u257 ?\u7693 ?h\u257 ? and \u346 ?rava\u7751 ?a) completed the symbolic circle of twenty-eight, representing a closed, perfect cycle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The ancient Indian calendar assigned these 28 lunar mansions unequal extents measured in {\i muh\u363 ?rtas} (48-minute segments):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 16 nak\u7779 ?atras: 30 muh\u363 ?rtas each\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 6 nak\u7779 ?atras: 45 muh\u363 ?rtas each\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 5 nak\u7779 ?atras: 15 muh\u363 ?rtas each\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 nak\u7779 ?atra (Abhijit): 6 muh\u363 ?rtas\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As Indian astronomy encountered the solar calendar in the early centuries CE, mathematicians reduced the count from 28 to 27\u8212-a necessity because 360\u176 ? divides evenly by 27 (13\u176 ?20\u8242 ? per mansion) but not by 28 (\u8776 ?12\u176 ?51\u8242 ?). The adoption of 27 also enabled subdivision into four {\i padas} (quarters), yielding 108 total padas\u8212-a number that became sacred in both Buddhist and Hindu numerology. Yet the archaic 28-count persisted in cosmological and liturgical contexts, preserving its symbolic weight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Archaeological evidence confirms the antiquity and pan-Asian reach of this framework. The lacquered wooden box found in the tomb of Marquis Yi of Zeng (433 BCE) bears the names of the twenty-eight constellations in seal script, demonstrating that this astronomical system crossed cultural and linguistic boundaries along ancient trade routes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In Buddhist cosmology, this astronomical reality was adopted to illustrate the vastness of the universe and the rhythmic appearance of enlightened beings across infinite aeons. By aligning sacred literature with the twenty-eight-fold division of the heavens, early Buddhist redactors imbued their texts with cosmic authority. The {\i Dhamma} was thus positioned not as a local or temporal phenomenon but as a universal constant, mirroring the precision of celestial mechanics.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 3. The Twenty-Eight Buddhas of the Buddhava\u7747 ?sa\par}
