{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 4. The Lotus S\u363 ?tra: Twenty-Eight Chapters as Cosmic Structure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.1 Kum\u257 ?raj\u299 ?va\u8217's Standardization\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\i Lotus S\u363 ?tra} exists in multiple translations, but Kum\u257 ?raj\u299 ?va\u8217's version (406 CE) became definitive in East Asia. Significantly, Kum\u257 ?raj\u299 ?va standardized the text at {\b twenty-eight chapters}, whereas Dharmarak\u7779 ?a\u8217's earlier translation (286 CE) contained only twenty-seven (Reeves 2008: 1\u8211-15).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This standardization was not merely editorial but reflects the \u8220"cultural and cosmological gravity\u8221" of the number twenty-eight. By aligning the s\u363 ?tra with this sacred number, Kum\u257 ?raj\u299 ?va facilitated its acceptance as a \u8220"complete\u8221" and perfect scripture.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.2 Zhiyi\u8217's Tiantai Exegesis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Chinese Tiantai patriarch Zhiyi (538\u8211-597) provided the definitive interpretation of the twenty-eight-chapter structure, dividing the text into two equal halves:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Trace Teaching (Chapters 1\u8211-14)} \u8212- {\i jimen} / {\i shakumon} - Focuses on the historical \u346 ?\u257 ?kyamuni Buddha - Expounds the doctrine of \u8220"One Vehicle\u8221" ({\i ekay\u257 ?na}) - Reveals that diverse paths (\u347 ?r\u257 ?vakas, pratyekabuddhas, bodhisattvas) are \u8220"skillful means\u8221" leading to unified enlightenment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Fundamental Teaching (Chapters 15\u8211-28)} \u8212- {\i benmen} / {\i honmon} - Centers on the \u8220"Eternal Buddha\u8221" - Reveals the immeasurable lifespan of the Buddha\u8212-enlightened since the infinite past - Emphasizes the bodhisattva way in the present age\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Zhiyi\u8217's famous metaphor: the fundamental teaching is the moon in the sky; the trace teaching is the moon reflected in a lake. The eternal Buddha (source) manifests as the historical Buddha (reflection).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.3 Visual Manifestation: Jeweled Pagoda Mandalas\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The sacred nature of the twenty-eight-chapter structure is visually manifest in Japanese {\i Kinji h\u333 ?t\u333 ? mandara} (Jeweled Pagoda Mandalas). In these works, the entire text of the {\i Lotus S\u363 ?tra}\u8212-all twenty-eight chapters\u8212-is transcribed in minute golden characters forming the shape of a reliquary pagoda. The twenty-eight chapters become the literal \u8220"body\u8221" of the cosmic Buddha (Strong 2004: 143\u8211-67).\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 5. The Buddhacarita: Twenty-Eight Cantos\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A\u347 ?vagho\u7779 ?a\u8217's {\i Buddhacarita} (2nd century CE), the first systematic biography of the Buddha in Sanskrit {\i mah\u257 ?k\u257 ?vya} style, comprises exactly {\b twenty-eight cantos}. While the original Sanskrit preserves only the first fourteen, the complete text survives in Chinese and Tibetan translations (Cowell 1894: ix\u8211-xii).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The choice of twenty-eight cantos aligns the Buddha\u8217's biography with the same numerological template found in the {\i Buddhava\u7747 ?sa} and {\i Lotus S\u363 ?tra}. The Buddha\u8217's life becomes a complete and perfect cycle, mirroring the astronomical progression of the lunar mansions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The twenty-eighth canto, \u8220"The Division of the Relics,\u8221" marks the final stage of the Buddha\u8217's physical presence, concluding the narrative with the dispersion of his essence across the world\u8212-a textual parallel to the moon completing its cycle through all twenty-eight mansions.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
