{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 7.2 John Brough\u8217's Analysis of G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Brough\u8217's edition of the {\i G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? Dharmapada} (Brough 1962) establishes that the G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? text originally contained approximately {\b twenty-six chapters with four lost} (XXIII\u8211-XXVI). His analysis revealed several key organizing principles:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Principle of Decreasing Length}: Brough observed that chapters in the G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? recension appear sequenced in decreasing order of length\u8212-the scribe front-loaded the most extensive thematic collections (Brough 1962: 23\u8211-27).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Chapter 14 Gap}: A significant empty space of approximately 1.5 inches occurs at the end of Chapter 14 ({\i Pa\u7751 ?\u7693 ?ita}), marking the physical transition point where the scribe flipped the birch-bark strip to continue on the verso side. This mechanical midpoint confirms intentional structural planning (Brough 1962: 35).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The \u8220"Core 26\u8221" Hypothesis}: Brough identifies that the P\u257 ?li Dhammapada, the Ud\u257 ?navarga, and the G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? Dharmapada share a \u8220"common ancestor\u8221" structure typically centered on {\b 26 chapters}. The Chinese {\i Fa-chu ching} (224 CE) supports this: it contains a core of 26 chapters to which 13 additional chapters were appended, yielding 39 total (Brough 1962: 44\u8211-48).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Crucially, Brough notes that G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? is a \u8220"distinct recension,\u8221" not a primitive ancestor. The first three G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? chapters ({\i Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?a}, {\i Bhik\u7779 ?u}, {\i T\u7771 ?\u7779 ?\u7751 ?\u257 ?}) appear in {\b reversed order} as the final three chapters of the P\u257 ?li version\u8212-strong evidence of structural fluidity across traditions (Brough 1962: 51).\par}
