{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Critical observation}: The P\u257 ?li {\i Dhammapada} has {\b no dedicated chapter on Nirv\u257 ?\u7751 ?a}\u8212-the central soteriological goal. Samsara has a chapter. Nirvana does not. The {\i Ud\u257 ?navarga}, by contrast, preserves a distinct {\i Nirv\u257 ?\u7751 ?avarga} (Norman 1983: 75). This suggests that a {\i Nibb\u257 ?navagga} may have been {\b merged into Chapter 26} during transmission.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If we hypothesize: 1. A dedicated {\i Nibb\u257 ?navagga} (verses 383\u8211-386 + 410\u8211-423) 2. A distinct {\i Tath\u257 ?gatavagga} (expanded from the brief {\i Buddhavagga}, Ch. 14)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The result is a {\b twenty-eight-chapter} {\i Dhammapada}\u8212-aligning with the pan-Buddhist numerological pattern.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 7.4 Supporting Evidence: The Mah\u257 ?saddan\u299 ?ti\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\i Mah\u257 ?saddan\u299 ?ti}, a monumental P\u257 ?li grammar attributed to Aggava\u7747 ?sa (12th century), consists of exactly {\b twenty-eight chapters}. This suggests that Buddhist redactors and scholars viewed twenty-eight as a \u8220"canonical\u8221" number for complete, authoritative works (Warder 2000: 312).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 7.5 Defeat Conditions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the spirit of epistemic rigor, this hypothesis would be decisively weakened by:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b Discovery of explicit 26-chapter structures}: If G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ? or Patna recensions explicitly preserve a 26-chapter format with no evidence of merger or loss\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b Alternative explanation for Chapter 26\u8217's length}: Scholarly consensus that the {\i Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?avagga}\u8217's 41 verses result from accretion rather than merger\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b Late composition of Nibb\u257 ?na verses}: Philological evidence that verses 383\u8211-386 and 410\u8211-423 were composed significantly later than the chapter\u8217's core material\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab {\b Counter-examples}: Discovery of major Buddhist texts deliberately avoiding the 28-structure would weaken the \u8220"intentional architecture\u8221" thesis\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 7.6 Alternative Explanations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This study acknowledges competing interpretations:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Coincidence hypothesis}: Twenty-eight may simply be a culturally significant \u8220"round number\u8221" without deep intentionality behind each instantiation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Pattern-matching bias}: Humans are prone to finding patterns; the convergence of 28s may reflect selective attention rather than deliberate design\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Practical transmission}: Editorial decisions may have been driven by physical manuscript constraints (as Brough 1962: 35 notes for G\u257 ?ndh\u257 ?r\u299 ?) rather than cosmological intent\sa180\par}
